{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 15:34:04.825343", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and approach\n- Verified end-to-end reachability, routing, and basic transport from hosts to server farm.\n- Validated DNS and HTTP behavior to the advertised services and load balancer.\n- Probed server-side listeners and services, and inspected server-access L2/L3 state.\n\nKey findings\n\n1) Routing and reachability\n- OSPF health: Distribution routers and the server_access_router have consistent OSPF routes for 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, and 10.200.0.0/24 in line with the design.\n  - router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1: 10.200.0.0/24 learned via appropriate core links.\n  - server_access_router: 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 learned via 172.16.0.10; 10.200.0.0/24 directly on br0.\n- Host addressing and gateway:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 = 10.1.1.10/24, gw 10.1.1.1; host_2_1_1_1 = 10.2.1.10/24, gw 10.2.1.1. Both leases are dynamic (via DHCP), indicating DHCP relay/assignments are functioning.\n- ICMP reachability:\n  - Hosts can ping server farm nodes and the load balancer (e.g., host->10.200.0.6 and host->10.200.0.7 show 0% loss, low RTT).\n  - Backend network isolation: Hosts cannot reach 20.200.0.0/24 (e.g., ping 20.200.0.1 returns “Destination Net Unreachable” from dist gateways). This matches the design that backend web servers are not directly accessible.\n\n2) DNS resolution\n- Name lookups for web99.local, web0.local, web1.local succeed with low name lookup times in curl outputs; DNS is functioning from both hosts.\n\n3) HTTP application behavior\n- Load balancer (web99.local):\n  - host_1_1_1_1: total ~1.02–1.20 s; host_2_1_1_1: total ~1.03–1.11 s. Consistent and reachable. This suggests the LB path is healthy.\n- Web servers:\n  - web0.local, web1.local: Reachable from both hosts; however, response times vary (some requests ~1.0 s, others ~2.0–2.2 s).\n  - web3.local: Failing from both hosts with 10 s timeouts, despite ICMP reachability and TCP port 80 accepting connections.\n    Evidence:\n    - From hosts: curl to http://web3.local times out (twice, 10s each).\n    - From same subnet peers:\n      - server_access_router -> http://10.200.0.6: first timed out, later returned HTTP/1.0 200 OK (BaseHTTP/0.6 Python/3.11.2) with very large body.\n      - load_balancer -> http://10.200.0.6: timed out.\n      - web_server_0 -> port 80 TCP connect succeeds, but HTTP GET via curl times out.\n    - On web_server_3:\n      - Port 80 is listening from python3, not Apache: “LISTEN 0.0.0.0:80 users:((\"python3\",pid=43,fd=3))”\n      - Apache is not running: apache2.service Active: inactive (dead).\n      - Local curl http://127.0.0.1/ returns 200 OK from BaseHTTP with very large payload (thousands of bytes).\n    Interpretation:\n    - The HTTP service on web_server_3 is a Python BaseHTTP server (single-threaded) returning a very large response. It intermittently responds locally and to one peer but frequently times out to other peers within the same subnet. TCP connections establish (SYN/ACK), but no timely response is sent for many requests, consistent with a single-threaded server being busy generating/sending a large payload and not accepting/servicing additional requests.\n    - This is an application-layer problem on web_server_3, not a network forwarding/filtering issue (ICMP OK, TCP connect OK, INPUT policy ACCEPT, no firewall drops observed, same-subnet ARP entries present).\n\n4) Service configuration state on all web servers\n- web_server_0, web_server_1, web_server_2: Apache is also inactive (dead) on each; yet port 80 is listening.\n- This indicates that all “web_server_X” nodes are not running the intended Apache HTTP service and are likely running alternate listeners (e.g., Python HTTP server). This mismatch can explain higher and inconsistent response times on web0/local and web1/local and is the direct cause of web3/local unreliability.\n\n5) L2/L3 on server_access_router\n- br0 bridges all server interfaces; 10.200.0.1/24 on br0; ARP table shows STALE entries for web servers and LB (normal).\n- INPUT/FORWARD/OUTPUT policies ACCEPT; no filtering impediments observed.\n- Connectivity inside the 10.200.0.0/24 segment is healthy at L2/L3.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Critical: web3.local (10.200.0.6) HTTP service is intermittently unresponsive and frequently times out for clients, despite network reachability. Root symptom: application-level issue on web_server_3.\n- Systemic misconfiguration: Apache not running on web_server_0–3 contrary to the stated design; alternate process (python3 BaseHTTP) is bound to port 80 on these servers.\n- Performance variability: web0.local and web1.local show elevated/variable total times (~2 s on many attempts), consistent with non-optimized single-threaded HTTP serving large content.\n\nFault localization\n- Primary faulty device: web_server_3 (10.200.0.6). The issue is localized to the application process listening on TCP/80 (python3 BaseHTTP) and its behavior under load/content size.\n- Secondary configuration deviations: web_server_0, web_server_1, web_server_2, where the intended Apache service is not active and port 80 is served by a non-Apache process, leading to suboptimal performance.\n\nLikely root cause\n- Misconfiguration of the web servers: Apache HTTP Server is not running (inactive) on all web servers. On web_server_3 specifically, a single-threaded Python BaseHTTP server is serving a very large response, causing new connections from peers to establish but not receive timely HTTP responses, producing client-side timeouts. There is no evidence of routing, OSPF, or firewall issues causing the failures.\n\nAdditional notes\n- Load balancer function appears normal, and backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is correctly not reachable from hosts, consistent with design.\n- DNS resolution is healthy for tested hostnames.\n\nNo remediation steps are provided at this stage per instructions.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 18709, "output_tokens": 4665, "total_tokens": 23374, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 18176}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3136}}}
